      <div xml:id="NA27-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu (ET: talaivaṉ) ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi ceṟippaṟivuṟīiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante informs [him] of [HER] confinement when [HE] was behind the fence.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA27">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nīyum yāṉu nerunaṟ pūvi</l>
<l>            ṉuṇṭā tiṟaikkum vaṇṭiṉa mōppi</l>
<l>            yoḻitirai varitta veṇmaṇa laṭaikaraik</l>
<l>            kaḻicūḻ kāṉa lāṭiya taṉṟik</l>
<l>            karantunāñ ceyta toṉṟillai yuṇṭeṉiṟ </l>
<l>            parantupiṟa raṟintaṉṟu milarē naṉṟu</l>
<l>            mevaṉkuṟit taṉaḷko laṉṉai kayantō</l>
<l>            ṟiṟavā riṉakkuru kolippac cuṟavaṅ</l>
<l>            kaḻicēr maruṅkiṟ kaṇaikkā ṉīṭik</l>
<l>            kaṇpōṟ pūttamai kaṇṭu nuṇpala </l>
<l>            ciṟupā caṭaiya neytal</l>
<l>            kuṟumō ceṉṟeṉak kūṟā tōḷē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">

<l>You and me, yesterday, besides driving away</l>
<l rend="indent">groups of bees, that were dispersing the fine flower pollen,</l>
<l rend="indent">[and] dancing in the seashore grove surrounded by backwaters</l>
<l rend="indent">on the shore where white sand settles, marked by subsiding(?)<note place="foot">Here we might consider <term xml:lang="ta">oḻi tirai</term> as a misspelling of the formulaic <term xml:lang="ta">oli tirai</term>.</note> waves</l>
<l>there is not a thing done by us secretly.</l>
<l rend="indent4">If they say it is,</l>
<l>there are no others to have spread [this] from knowledge.
    <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṟintaṉṟum</term>: here we have to analyse the perfective neuter singular as a verbal noun, despite the seemingly finite form. There is quite a number of parallels for this type of negative construction with il to be found in the old anthologies except the KT (cf. NA 130.10, 147.9, 175.6, 193.5, 237.5, 239.9; AN 19.1, 32.15, 101.18, 190.17, 346.12; PN 61.17, 77.7, 10, 192.5, 257.5, 6, 333.13). We might understand this as a fomation analogous to the frequent verbal noun in -(t)al + negation in -il (as is nicely illustrated by PN 192, where we find two consecutive lines containing both forms: <term xml:lang="ta">makiḻntaṉṟum ilamē ... eṉṟalum ilamē</term>). The –um adds the nuance of completeness here, which could be translated literally: "others are not for knowing anything at all". An additional problem is posed by <term xml:lang="ta">parantu</term> here, since we would expect that something has to be known before it can be spread, in other words, the sequence should be: <term xml:lang="ta">aṟintu parantaṉṟum</term>.</note>
</l>
<l>What was quite on mother's mind?</l>
<l>– who did not tell [us] to go [and] pluck<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kuṟumō ceṉṟu</term>: the only way to make sense of this is to accept a reverse of word order. One would like parallels for this kind of post-positioned absolutive.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">blue waterlilies with tiny green leaves,</l>
<l rend="indent2">fine [and] many<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nuṇpala</term> can be connected either with <term xml:lang="ta">aṭaiya</term> or with <term xml:lang="ta">neytal</term>.</note>, at the sight of [their] blossoming just like eyes,</l>
<l rend="indent2">grown on round stems at a side where sharks join in the backwaters,</l>
<l>while the herons are clamouring, flocks feeding on prawn in every pond.</l>
        </lg>
